This principle Manilius illustrates in the case of the first and third triangles‚ where the causes of hostility are most clearly seen (523 —38). b'But it follows necessarily from 520- 2 that the same principle governs the relations of the second and fourth triangles also—quamam spatio exclusus de posterioribus lzz's ni'lzzl discent (Ellis). In what follows—539-4o—Manilius says that though all signs obey this law of triangular opposition‚ yet a good many of them wage wars of their own ( priuata arma); and in 541-69 he gives a list of all the enmities of each sign, whether private enmities or enmities arising out of triangular situation.
